      <div class="slides">
        <section>
          <h1>DepSim</h1>
          <h3>By Alex Schneider</h3>
          <h4>CMSI 402 Spring 2016</h4>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h1>Description</h1>
          <ul>
            <li>Modeling language to represent deployments across largely distributed systems consisting of millions of individual processing entities</li>
            <li>Simulation that takes the model definition and optimizes to find the best deployment strategy</li>
            <li>Graphical interface that displays the results of the optimizations</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h1>Goals</h1>
          <ul>
            <li>Improve rollout strategy for software updates while minimizing the risk of catastrophic failure</li>
            <li>Look for patterns and refine current methodologies for managing distributed systems</li>
            <li>Gain experience with thinking about largely distributed systems prior to starting at Microsoft</li>
            <li>Use as a contrivance to enter the research environment at Microsoft after I start there</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h1>Justification</h1>
          <ul>
            <li>Unique problem that most computer science students don't come across in their curriculum</li>
            <li>Has a great deal of future work or research down the line</li>
            <li>Gain some domain knowledge prior to beginning my job</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Parts of the LMU Curriculum</h2>
          <small>
          <table>
            <tr>
              <td>
                Theory of Computation,<br />Language Translation and Implementation
              </td>
              <td>
                Designing and building a modeling  language
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                Probability and Statistics
              </td>
              <td>
                Processing and analyzing the data arising from the simulations
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>
                Interaction Design
              </td>
              <td>
                Designing and developing UI components and representing data in a graphical form
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
          </small>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h1>User Interface</h1>
          <img class="stretch" src="https://i.imgur.com/7bgWKsB.png">
          <ul>
            <li><small>Running the app starts a locally hosted web server and automatically opens the browser (soon to be a PyQT application using PyWebkit for a more native experience</small></li>
          </ul>
          <small><b>Note:</b> Simulation results interface not yet complete</small>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h1>Technologies Used</h1>
          <ul>
            <li>PyParsing - Recursive descent parsing library for Python</li>
            <li>SimPy - Discrete event simulation library for Python</li>
            <li>Bottle - Locally host web application for the user interface</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
          <section>
            <h1>Problems</h1>
            <ul>
              <li>Distributed systems on this scale were hard to comprehend and wrap my head around. There's also not much documentation</li>
              <li>I've never done any type of discrete event simulation project so that was a large learning curve</li>
              <li>Frequent breaking changes on libraries (more on this next slide)</li>
          </section>
          <section>
            <h1>Problems (with PyParsing)</h1>
            <ul>
              <li>Documentation is inconsistent and incomplete</li>
              <li>Breaking changes</li>
            </ul>
            <img class="stretch" src="http://i.imgur.com/T3z0Mtd.png">
          </section>
          <section>
            <img class="stretch" src="http://i.imgur.com/4i1OMSZ.png">
          </section>
        </section>

